  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT276-kilavi">tōḻikkuk kuṟaimaṟāmal talaimakaṉ kūṟiyatu. </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">HE speaking to the confidante, that [she] may not refuse
          [his] request. </p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT276">
          <l> paṇaittōṭ kuṟumakaḷ pāvai taiiyum</l>
          <l> pañcāyp paḷḷañ cūḻntu maṟṟiva</l>
          <l> ḷurutteḻu vaṉamulai yoḷipeṟa veḻutiya</l>
          <l> toyyil kāppō raṟitalu maṟiyār</l>
          <l> muṟaiyuṭai yaracaṉ ceṅkō lavaiyat</l>
          <l> tiyāṉṟaṟ kaṭaviṉ yāṅkā vatukol</l>
          <l> peritum pētai maṉṟa</l>
          <l> vaḷitō tāṉēyiv vaḻuṅka lūrē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l>Those who keep watch [on her] have no idea <note place="foot">
              <term xml:lang="ta">aṟital aṟiyār</term> : the nuance of the figura etymologica is
            presumably emphasis/intensification? For a parallel see NA 106.1.</note> of the sandal
            paste,</l>
          <l rend="indent">which, to obtain brightness,</l>
          <l rend="indent6">she has drawn on [her] shapely rising pretty breasts,</l>
          <l rend="indent2">nor also just <note place="foot">How to understand the construction with <term xml:lang="ta">maṟṟu </term> here? For another possibility see 2-4c.</note> that the
            ditch is surrounded by Pañcāy grass <note place="foot">Or <term xml:lang="ta">cūḻ-tal </term>
            DEDR 2735 "to deliberate, consider, select ...": "that the Pañcāy grass ditch has been
            selected [as a meeting point]". The point about the ditch must be in any case that the
            lovers have met there.</note>
          </l>
          <l rend="indent2">nor also <note place="foot">These four lines definitely look as if three
            unknown facts have been coordinated with <term xml:lang="ta">-um</term> , though the
            construction seems anacolouthic.</note> that an image of the small woman with bamboo</l>
          <l rend="indent9">shoulders has been fashioned. <note place="foot">This topos of the image
            which is made by the girl is strange and attested several times. Does this allude to an
            unknown social symbolism? (Cf. KT 48.1, 89.6, 100.6, 114.1, 279.3, 292.4).</note> </l>
          <l>If I urged <note place="foot">Or up to line 6 inclusively this is one sentence, and
            “those who keep watch on her, but do not know”, are the direct object to <term xml:lang="ta">kaṭaviṉ </term> ("If I urged those, who ...).</note>
          </l>
          <l rend="indent2">in the assembly under the impartial staff of a just king, <note place="foot">
              <term xml:lang="ta">muṟaiyuṭai </term> is glossed by Cām. as <term xml:lang="ta">
            nītiyaiyuṭaiya</term> , "just".</note></l>
          <l rend="indent6">what would happen?</l>
          <l>And great [is] folly indeed.</l>
          <l>Ah, it seems <note place="foot">Here again the problem is the nuance conveyed by -ō.
            Even if -ō in a certain number of formula has originally been one of mourning, if seems
            likely that in some cases it is just transmitted with the formula. Of course one might
            argue here, that it is used in an ironical sense.</note> pitiful, this noisy village.</l>

          <lg type="alternate" sameAs="1-4b" resp="#TVG">
            <l>Those who keep watch [on her] have no idea of</l>
            <l>[my] fashioning a doll for the small woman with bamboo shoulders</l>
            <l>[and my] selecting (for this purpose) Pañcāy grass from the ditch,</l>
            <l>[and] of the sandal paste I have drawn on [her] ... breasts, <note place="foot">Thus
              T.V.G.'s interpretation who asserts that HE uses the grass to fashion a doll for HER,
              and moreover he is the one who paints her breasts. If, however, attention is paid to
              the "expletive" <term xml:lang="ta"> maṟṟu</term> , followed by <term xml:lang="ta">
              ivaḷ</term> , which presumably marks a change of subject, yet another rendering is
              more likely (i.e. 2+3c).</note>
            </l>

            <lg type="alternate" sameAs="2-4c">
              <l>and furthermore of the sandal paste she has pressed, so that it is</l>
              <l>clearly visible, [from my chest] <note place="foot">Perhaps the clue to this
                seemingly strange piece of information lies in <term xml:lang="ta">toyyil</term> ,
                the sandal paste. Usually it is HIS chest which is said to be smeared with sandal
                paste. So the point might be that in their embrace SHE has got her share also of his
                sandal paste.</note> onto [her] ... breasts,</l>
            </lg>
          </lg>

        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
